<br>
Thank you for clarifying this, Candy, because that is an important differentiation.  For whatever reason, ST, you acted defensively and not at all in the reasonable manner that I usually associate with your arguements.  I didn't hear anyone say that a woman should not work, period.  Some parents work because they have to, some do because they perform a vital service to the public, others because they enjoy the mental and social stimulation that working outside the home can offer.  There's nothing wrong with any of this, imo.  It's when I hear about a couple who dump their kids off on a nanny or in daycare for 10 hours a day, five days a week not because they need the money to survive, but because they find parenting a small child just a little too difficult or inconvenient that makes me wonder, Well then, why the hell did you bother?  These kids are only here because we put them here, and every one of them deserves better than that, from their moms AND dads.  That' all I'm sayin'.<br>
As for the sexism issue, I can only refer to the experience of my own family where the women always worked.  My grandmothers and my mother all worked because they had to.  But my mom and dad made darn sure that us kids were never without them for more than an hour or so, even when it meant working graveyard shifts or, as my mom did when I was a toddler, cleaning houses for rich folks so I could come to work with her.  We make these kinds of sacrifices for our kids because they are our responsibility.  And that's where I'm coming from.<br>
<br>
By the bye, on the sharing household duties: Dh is the kitchen man, he cleans it and does the dishes.  If he's home he'll sometimes cook (on workdays he gets home too late).  I do laundry and general cleaning, vaccuuming, etc.  We pretty much split up yard work.  After dinner, I consider myself mostly off the parental clock, except now that we have 2 kiddies we divide and conquer at bedtime.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
-Simone<br>
