<br>
DBC then said that being at work all day is a “way different order of pressure” than what a SAHM parent has, which is to say it is much less stressful to work than be at home. I took issue with this, just as many of you took issue with me saying I think being home is less stressful. If you equate stress with importance or value, you have bought into the mysoginistic, corporate mindset that eats away at the very credibility of socially important work in general and that’s too bad. When I typed that message out, I was actually thinking it was nice which is why I compared it to teaching, which I also found less stressful but far more important than corporate/technical work. But ya know—it’s not the double standard here I find most alarming…the fact that it’s okay to say SAHM’s have so much more stress but I can’t disagree…it’s the gratuitous, bullshit backpeddling going on by those who clearly stated that having children with no intent to quit work is selfish and these people have no right to have kids. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Candy—you didn’t direct your statement toward me? Odd because since you know both my dh and I work full time you know our kids are in daycare 50 hours a week. You did specify the hours in your post right? So to be clear, you WERE indeed saying parents like myself (more specifically mothers who choose to work) are &quot;dumping&quot; their kids off and &quot;why did they have kids anyway&quot; right?  <br>
If you feel kids in daycare are neglected or somehow receive less parenting, than whether we choose to work or not doesn’t change the fact that the children are suffering either so by that token all single working parents are also “dumping kids off” and not raising them. You can say it's a shame these children get sub-par parenting, but I think it's time you back that up with more than your opinion and stop differentiating by choice. If 50 hours of daycare is harmful, then it's harmful regardless of why mommy is at work. <br>
<br>
powertotherae--I understand about any parent staying home, but your statement would still apply to me and it was a general one, not one that said each should do what is best, if that's not what you meant than I'm glad, but I'm not sure what you did mean in that post. Perhaps since I am not part time and my dh works also I am still irresponsible and unworthy in your eyes, I cannot tell.<br>
<br>
As I have mentioned before, this is a DEBATE board, not a support one and since there has been not one shred of actual evidence yet provided here either way, and since there is clearly a double standard as to what can be said about what is stressful or fits each family, it is quite silly to claim there are winners or losers. <br>
<br>
I clearly got personal, but tried to be clear who I was directing it toward and had no intention of rebuffing an argument since no logical one has been made. Candy can say all she wants that working parents who put their children in daycare 50 hours a week don’t deserve children (like me), but where was the evidence data for her argument? Who was she being supportive of with that statement? Only the very next post even addressed it, so was her post so much less offensive than mine saying staying at home was less stressful? In what way? Did I ever say any SAHP's don't have the right to children or that children of SAHP's are receiving less parenting? You would think so reading through this thread. Was the &quot;workaholic&quot; and &quot;why bother&quot; not a nasty little comment in the first place? None of you seem to think so, but this is indeed subjective. <br>
<br>
If me telling her to fuck off offends some here, then I am sorry for that<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :o --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/embarassed.gif ALT=":o"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> …didn’t realize profanity was now forbidden since DBC often tells Candy her arguments are bullshit and I never minded that myself. Had this been an actual argument or debate where points and data were being presented this would have been Ad hominem Maximus and still is really, but when someone tells me I shouldn't have bothered to have kids they can fuck off, so you're right, this was just gut reaction...perhaps Candy wishes to make an actual point we can debate and I'll promise to forgo the logical fallacies.<br>
<br>
Again—my comments about stress WERE stated as personal experience and on the heels of my ACTUAL original post in support of individual decision and I specifically stated I hate prescribed gender roles and telling women their education is wasted. Anyone misunderstanding that and getting upset is unfortunate and I’m sorry for that too…but that is a different issue than the 2 ladies who are making specific statements about the worthiness of other parents and while my language may be too offensive for some on this board, I stand by the sentiment directed at anyone who feels she is a superior mother to women who &quot;choose&quot; to work or feels her kids are getting betther mothering than mothers who work regardless of circumstance. Hope you're always lucky enough not to have to work Candy so your kids don't have to be &quot;dumped&quot; in daycare all week.<br>
