 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Mony</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(5/3/03 9:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=48>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Debate</span><hr size=1> &quot;...this is a DEBATE board, not a support one and since there has been not one shred of actual evidence yet provided here either way...&quot;<br>
<br>
I've been tooling around on the 'net, and many of the &quot;experts&quot; on various websites say there is no study proving one way or another whether child care--or how much--is good or bad for young children.  The NIH conducted a study in the 90's of 1300 children which stated:<br>
<br>
[r]esearchers found that the amount of nonmaternal child care was weakly associated with less sensitive and engaged mother-child interactions. The more time infants and toddlers spent in non-maternal child-care arrangements, the less sensitive and positively involved were mothers with their infants at 6 months of age, the more negative they were with them at 15 months of age, the less positively affectionate the child was toward the mother at 24 and 36 months of age, and the less sensitive mothers were to their toddlers at the 36 month point.<br>
[<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.nih.gov/news/pr/apr97/nichd-03.htm">www.nih.gov/news/pr/apr97/nichd-03.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->]<br>
<br>
However, the study focused mostly on what constituted high quality child care, as the variables involved with mother-child bonding (i.e. family environment, education, financial status, etc) were too great, I believe, to make broad statements about the effects of child care in general.  They did state, however, that  &quot;[t]hey found that child care, in and of itself, neither adversely affects, nor promotes, the security of children's attachment to their mothers at the 15 month age point, provided the children were already receiving relatively sensitive care from their mothers.&quot;<br>
<br>
-Simone <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=powertotherae>Powertotherae</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Satan's Lil' Minion</span><br>  Posts: 269<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/3/03 9:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=196.topic&index=49>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: re: Who Deserves to Have Children</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>powertotherae--I understand about any parent staying home, but your statement would still apply to me and it was a general one, not one that said each should do what is best, if that's not what you meant than I'm glad, but I'm not sure what you did mean in that post. Perhaps since I am not part time and my dh works also I am still irresponsible and unworthy in your eyes, I cannot tell.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
