<br>
&quot;So I honestly cannot understand what the purpose of having children would be for me if I couldn’t be there all the time. I also don’t want to share the joy of my children with anyone (except of course my dh).&quot;<br>
<br>
I don't know how old your kids are, but do any of them go to preschool or kindergarten, and do you plan to send them to regular school instead of homeschooling?  I was just wondering where you draw the line at sharing the joy of your children with someone else, and if there is some magic age where it's OK for you to not be with them 24 hrs. a day.  I'm not trying to be sarcastic here, I just don't understand what you mean by that.<br>
<br>
&quot;All I hear are my friend’s horror stories and that is what sticks in my mind.&quot;<br>
<br>
What kinds of horror stories?  Are they really all bad--no good ones?  I've had my dd in the same home daycare 3 days/wk for 2 years (she is now almost 3) and I have not one horror story to tell.  My daycare provider is wonderful and dd loves it there.  She is an only child and the social skills she has learned from being with the other kids has been invaluable.  She has a blast with her little friends and talks about them all the time.  She has been sick a total of one time in 2 years.  I have no doubt that this arrangement is better for her than if I stayed home with her full-time--can you understand why I feel that way in this situation?<br>
<br>
&quot;I have friends who don’t work but have full time nannies so they don’t have to be tied down.&quot;<br>
<br>
No great insights here--you just must have richer friends than I do! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
